				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">3gengames wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Why do we want a human readable format? What is so great about those that I'm apparently missing?</div><br /><br />Extensibility, Metadata. There are problems with human readable formats, but all the problems it has also exist in binary formats. I personally don't like memorizing which arbitrary mapper number corresponds to which board/mapper chip. Some boards don't have names and require a number, so I think some sort of mixed format would be optimal. Perhaps an extension to iNES that adds a block of XML metadata to the end of the file. This ensures that the new format is backwards compatible and allows for metadata in emulators that support it. Also if the XML metadata doesn't have the board name, you could fall back to the iNES mapper number. But since all revisions to iNES, and all new NES file formats are instantly met with a distilled hatred, it won't happen.<br /><br />EDIT: Also solves the problem for homebrew developers not having XML data in the internal database of whatever emulator. It decentralizes the metadata storage from emulators to game files. And any emu devs that detest the idea of having extra information about a game don't have to support it (Since it's at the end of the file, you don't even have to skip passed it). It's a perfect solution that no one should have a problem with.</div>

					
							<br /><br />
