				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And any emu devs that detest the idea of having extra information about a game don't have to support it (Since it's at the end of the file, you don't even have to skip passed it). It's a perfect solution that no one should have a problem with.</div><br /><br />If only.<br /><br />I tried storing coprocessor ROMs (that actually were inside the cart, and required for playing the games), and had half the internet go apeshit, including the MAME/MESS team that is so concerned with accuracy.<br /><br />Nach tried storing controller mapping information inside the SNES copier header field, which would cause koitsu to become tumultuous.<br /><br />Many emulators have tried using an internal and/or external database, to which developers like Nach vehemently oppose.<br /><br />When it comes to the idea of a separate file to describe part of the game ... just don't put the ROM+mapping into a folder. That's about the most controversial action in the entire world.<br /><br />Best bet would be to have: gamename.nes(iNES 1.0)+gamename.markup, and to distribute this as two files inside of a ZIP archive. Existing emulators can run the ZIP directly and not even know the markup is there, and extract+play still works. You'll still get complaints from everyone that nobody will ever adopt your format, and that you're wasting your time, and that it can never be relied on to be there, and so forth. Others will insist you should use .7z, or .jma, or .unif, or some new container format, or some other compression container.<br /><br />Finally, this format will be mired with years of debate. First, about which markup language to use. XML? JSON? YAML? INI? I went with BML: parses with ~3KB of code, no entities/escaping, no billion laughs attacks. Once you finally have consensus on the format, you'll argue about what each field should be named, whether we should use camelCase, under_scores or CapsCase, who should be allowed to define new information for the spec (which will result in incompatible forks of the format), etc.<br /><br />Have fun =)<br /><br />(FWIW, I do like this idea. I say whoever wants to do it should go for it, even if it doesn't catch on.)</div>

