						<div class="postbody">I tried making a human readable format a while ago that contained compressed data:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">u32 header_size;<br />byte data&#91; header_size &#93;;<br /><br />for every chip:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; u32 dump_size;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; byte data&#91; dump_size &#93;;<br /></div><br /><br />The header data and dump data for each chip is then decompressed individually and the header is parsed as XML. Was a simple format that allowed me to emulate 99% of games without hash checks, but when I mentioned this on IRC it was as if I said Hitler didn't go far enough. I don't get what's so special about iNES that it must be perfectly preserved in it's broken state, and any new formats must be backwards compatible with it.</div>

