						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The main game cartridge format ought to describe what's on the PCB in enough detail that a functionally equivalent reproduction can be built.</div>Yes; this is good. However, in <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/User:Zzo38/Metadata_INI" class="postlink">my format</a>, there is a bit of information which can be used to make a PCB (even though it is not needed, it can help), in the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">Mapper</tt> block; for example, if the game doesn't care about mirroring, this can be specified here.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">beannaich wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Was a simple format that allowed me to emulate 99% of games without hash checks, but when I mentioned this on IRC it was as if I said Hitler didn't go far enough.</div>My format has two things about such thing (and specifies that if the INI file exists, no hash checks should be made for purpose of klugy emulation): the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">Bootgod</tt> field of the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">Main</tt> block, and the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">Emulator</tt> block.<br /><br />My format is also simple (there are some complicated parts but none are required), extensible, has all parts optional, has no part that the program reading it is required, etc.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">byuu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">When it comes to the idea of a separate file to describe part of the game ... just don't put the ROM+mapping into a folder. That's about the most controversial action in the entire world.<br /><br />Best bet would be to have: gamename.nes(iNES 1.0)+gamename.markup, and to distribute this as two files inside of a ZIP archive. Existing emulators can run the ZIP directly and not even know the markup is there, and extract+play still works.</div>I agree and have designed my proposal in (almost) this way (although they are not required to be part of a same ZIP archive, but they obviously could be). It even allows multiple formats if you need more than one, for some purposes.<br /><br />However I would like comments of my proposed format too. (I may use it even if you don't, though.)</div>

					
